{"id":"10977","name":"Time Saved with Overcast","tagline":"Helps you track the hours that Smart Speed in Overcast saves you over time.","icon":"ios15 c4271458815 g59662","latest":"31679","description":"\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>This shortcut opens the <a href=\"https://overcast.fm\">Overcast app</a> and waits for you to find your time saved with Smart Speed (Overcast Settings → Scroll the bottom) and take a screenshot of that page. </p>\n<p>After you return to the Shortcuts app, it automatically finds the number of hours saved from the screenshot, then adds that new total and today’s date to a Numbers spreadsheet with the running results.</p>\n<p>After you review the results and return to the Shortcuts app again, it finishes by jumping to your task manager to complete the task and delete the screenshot.</p>\n<p>I find it’s best run from a URL in a reoccurring task. A blank Numbers spreadsheet can be downloaded <a href=\"https://heydingus.net/s/Time-Saved-with-Overcast.numbers\">here</a>.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://heydingus.net/shortcuts-tips/\">You can read about the creation of this shortcut on <em>HeyDingus</em>.</a></p>\n<p><em>Note: The Numbers action is not supported on Mac at the time of publishing, so it must be run from an iPad or iPhone.</em></p>\n\t\t\t\t","releasenotes":"<p><strong>1.2.1 - Feb. 3, 2022, 5:37 a.m.</strong></p><p>1.2.1 fixes a small typo in addition to the new features below.<br><br>- Changed the flow to use a screenshot and text extraction action to get the number of hours with the goal of being more automated and less error-prone.<br>- Updated comments and added notifications to be more clear about what is happening and is needed from the user at critical steps.</p>"}